DRIVER-2651 recently added new BSON corpus tests for Decimal128 where the {{degenerate_extjson}} representation uses very large exponent values.

POC-ing these tests with PHPC resulted in several failures converting the degenerate extJSON to Canonical BSON. The code path in PHPC's test runner directly utilizes libbson's {{bson_new_from_json()}} function.

The spec tests and details of the PHPC failures can be found in [mongodb/specifications#1432|https://github.com/mongodb/specifications/pull/1432#issuecomment-1592128172]. [~matt.dale@mongodb.com]'s assessment from [this #dbx-devs thread|https://mongodb.slack.com/archives/C72LB5RPV/p1686789749854299?thread_ts=1686783750.487309&cid=C72LB5RPV] is as follows:

{quote}
As far as the failures, the ones that failed with
{noformat}
-180000001364000000000000000000000000000000fe5f00
+180000001364000000000000000000000000000000000000
{noformat}
were expecting 0E+6111 but got 0E-6176.

The ones that failed with
{noformat}
-180000001364000000000000000000000000000000008000
+180000001364000000000000000000000000000000fedf00
{noformat}
were expecting 0E-6176 but got 0E+6111.

Seems like it could be some kind of exponent overflow/underflow problem.
{quote}

h4. Summary

Parsing
{code:java} [{"$code" : "A"}]{code}
results in BSON data with an unexpected "\xbe" key:
{code}% echo "0E0000000DBE0002000000410000" | ~/code/specifications/source/bson-corpus/tests/bsonview -x
 0e000000 0d "\xbe" 00 02000000 "A" 00 00
{code}
The same"\xbe" key appears for parsing $dbPointer.

The expected behavior is to parse to an array document with the key "0". The expected parsed BSON is to be equivalent to parsing:
{code:java}{"0" : {"$code" : "A"}} {code}
results in BSON data with the expected "0" key:
{code}% echo "0E0000000D300002000000410000" | ~/code/specifications/source/bson-corpus/tests/bsonview -x
 0e000000 0d "0" 00 02000000 "A" 00 00
{code}
h4. Environment

libbson 1.24.1 on macOS 12.6.7 arm64. Clang 16.0.5.
h4. How to Reproduce

Here is a branch with a failing test: [https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/compare/master...kevinAlbs:mongo-c-driver:code_parsing_bug?expand=1] :
{code}   // Test parsing `[ {"$code" : "A"} ]` and `{ "0": {"$code" : "A"} }`. Results
   // in incorrect unequal BSON.
   {
      bson_t *b1;
      {
         // Parsing `[ {"$code" : "A"} ]` results in an invalid key.
         const char *json = BSON_STR ([ {"$code" : "A"} ]);
         bson_error_t error;
         b1 = bson_new_from_json ((const uint8_t *) json, -1, &error);
         ASSERT_OR_PRINT (b1, error);
         printf ("bson parsed from %s:\n", json);
         dump_bson (b1);
      }

      bson_t *b2;
      {
         const char *json = BSON_STR ({"0" : {"$code" : "A"}});
         bson_error_t error;
         b2 = bson_new_from_json ((const uint8_t *) json, -1, &error);
         ASSERT_OR_PRINT (b2, error);
         printf ("bson parsed from %s:\n", json);
         dump_bson (b2);
      }

      ASSERT (bson_equal (b1, b2));
      bson_destroy (b2);
      bson_destroy (b1);
   }
{code}

h3. *Problem Statement/Rationale*

{color:#505f79}mongo-c-driver 1.24.1 fails to build because it can't find bson/bson-dsl.h. libbson 1.24.1 didn't install it. {color}
h3. *Steps to Reproduce*

I've installed libbson 1.24.1 built with these cmake flags:

{{-DENABLE_AUTOMATIC_INIT_AND_CLEANUP=OFF
-DENABLE_EXAMPLES=OFF
-DENABLE_TESTS=OFF
-DENABLE_UNINSTALL=OFF
-DMONGO_USE_CCACHE=OFF
-DENABLE_BSON=ON
-DENABLE_MONGOC=OFF}}

Then I tried to build mongo-c-driver 1.24.1 with these cmake flags:

{{{}-DENABLE_AUTOMATIC_INIT_AND_CLEANUP=OFF
-DENABLE_EXAMPLES=OFF
{}}}{{{}-DENABLE_TESTS=OFF
-DENABLE_UNINSTALL=OFF
-DMONGO_USE_CCACHE=OFF-DENABLE_ICU=ON
-DENABLE_MONGOC=ON
-DENABLE_SASL=CYRUS
-DENABLE_SNAPPY=ON
-DENABLE_ZLIB=SYSTEM
-DUSE_SYSTEM_LIBBSON=TRUE{}}}
h3. *Expected Results*

{color:#505f79}Successful build{color}
h3. *Actual Results*

{color:#505f79}Build failure:{color}

{color:#505f79}{{src/libmongoc/src/mongoc/mongoc-aggregate.c:26:10: fatal error: 'bson/bson-dsl.h' file not found}}
{{#include <bson/bson-dsl.h>}}
{{         ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~}}
{{1 error generated.}}
{color}
h3. *Additional Notes*

{color:#505f79}Another user previously reported the problem here:{color}

{color:#505f79}[https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/commit/40a64c2ffd6634021741e5435be15089d1f466f3#commitcomment-119488769]{color}

{color:#505f79}I'm on macOS 12.6.7 installing libbson and mongo-c-driver with MacPorts—I'm the maintainer of these in MacPorts, currently trying to update them from 1.23.5, which was fine, to 1.24.1.{color}

{color:#505f79}For 1.24.1 I'm using {color}{{-DUSE_SYSTEM_LIBBSON=TRUE}} instead of {{{}-DENABLE_BSON=SYSTEM{}}}; I hope I've correctly understood from the documentation that this is needed.

The spec changes of DRIVERS-578 says:

{quote}
Drivers MUST document the thread-safety and fork-safety limitations of sessions.
{quote}

But fork safety is not mentioned in the docs for [mongoc_client_session_t|http://mongoc.org/libmongoc/current/mongoc_client_session_t.html].

In general, depending on the outcome of CDRIVER-3116, it may be beneficial to document fork safety of mongoc_client_t in general (perhaps a page similar to [this one|http://mongoc.org/libbson/current/threading.html]).

h1. Summary

Setting the URI option {{socketTimeoutMS=-1}} results in an error in C driver 1.25.1 with the message: "timeout_msec value 4294967295 exceeds supported 32-bit range"

Here is a [test showing the issue|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/compare/master...kevinAlbs:mongo-c-driver:timeout_msec_exceeds?expand=1]:
{code:c}// Regression test for CDRIVER-4781.
static void
test_timeout_msec_exceeds (void)
{
   bson_error_t error;
   mongoc_uri_t *uri = test_framework_get_uri ();
   mongoc_uri_set_option_as_int32 (uri, MONGOC_URI_SOCKETTIMEOUTMS, -1);
   mongoc_client_t *client =
      mongoc_client_new_from_uri_with_error (uri, &error);
   ASSERT_OR_PRINT (client, error);
   test_framework_set_ssl_opts (client);
   bson_t *ping = BCON_NEW ("ping", BCON_INT32 (1));
   bool ok =
      mongoc_client_command_simple (client, "db", ping, NULL, NULL, &error);
   // On commit abb0bb7da8230d342dac5061623c1e4936ed46d9, results in error:
   // "timeout_msec value 4294967295 exceeds supported 32-bit range"
   // On prior commit 3e8a24311c21917420fd7fd2b00637deb4b168ce, results in
   // success.
   ASSERT_OR_PRINT (ok, error);
   bson_destroy (ping);
   mongoc_client_destroy (client);
   mongoc_uri_destroy (uri);
}
{code}
In versions <1.24.0, it was not an error. The error check was added in CDRIVER-4599.

{{4294967295}} is the result of casting {{-1}} as a {{{}uint32_t{}}}. {{mongoc_cluster_t::sockettimeoutms}} is represented as a {{{}uint32_t{}}}.

Proposal: support the value {{-1}} (and possibly negative values) for backwards compatibility. Document use of negative values as deprecated.
h1. Background & Motivation

This impacted a customer setting {{connectTimeoutMS}} to -1. Refer: [https://mongodb.slack.com/archives/C0V2T72R2/p1699631179298719]

h1. Open questions

1. In versions <1.24.0 was -1 interpreted as "no timeout" or "use default timeout"?
2. Is 0 considered "no timeout" in the C driver? [The URI spec|https://github.com/mongodb/specifications/blob/022fbf64fb36c80b9295ba93acec150c94362767/source/uri-options/uri-options.rst] specifies: 

{quote}
non-negative integer; 0 means no timeout
{quote}

But the [1.25.1 C driver documentation|https://mongoc.org/libmongoc/1.25.1/mongoc_uri_t.html] claims "0" means "apply the default":

{quote}
Setting any of the *timeoutMS options above to 0 will be interpreted as “use the default value”.
{quote}

The following functions in {{test-mongoc-sample-commands.c}} still use {{mongoc_collection_update()}}, which has been superseded by newer CRUD methods:

 * {{test_example_52}}
 * {{test_example_53}}
 * {{test_example_54}}

This code ends up in C driver examples published in the MongoDB manual, so it would be preferable to use the newer methods here.

*Background & Motivation*

C driver API which accepts a {{bson_t* reply}} expects the {{reply}} to be uninitialized. This is inconsistently documented. 

[mongoc_collection_command_simple|http://mongoc.org/libmongoc/current/mongoc_collection_command_simple.html] notes: 
{quote}
reply: A location to initialize a bson_t. This should be on the stack.
{quote}

[mongoc_database_command_simple|http://mongoc.org/libmongoc/current/mongoc_database_command_simple.html] notes:
{quote}
reply: A location to store the commands first result document.
{quote}

[mongoc_client_session_commit_transaction|http://mongoc.org/libmongoc/current/mongoc_client_session_commit_transaction.html] notes:
{quote}
reply: An optional uninitialized bson_t to receive the server reply, or NULL.
{quote}

*Scope*
Audit the documentation for all API methods that take a {{bson_t* reply}} and consistently document that the {{reply}} must be uninitialized and cannot be the pointer returned by {{bson_new}}.

